{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0ff44900-ad25-4f1a-a3ad-f307a74e703a","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a dotnet tool:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <!-- Required for dotnet tool packaging -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <RepositoryUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</RepositoryUrl>\n\n  <!-- Recommended -->\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**Key steps:**\n\n1. **`PackAsTool`** — this is the critical property that makes `dotnet pack` produce a tool package.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command name users will invoke.\n3. **Pack it:** `dotnet pack -c Release`\n4. **Push it:** `dotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg --api-key YOUR_KEY --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json`\n\n**Users then install with:**\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server   # runs via stdio\n```\n\nSince your server uses stdio transport, no additional configuration is needed — `dotnet tool` packages are console apps by nature, so stdin/stdout work as expected.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5798288b-f706-4552-9718-f83978dd3c85","outputTokens":464,"requestId":"843D:C2332:FF9F5B:140C161:69FFDB46"},"id":"1e303db5-d326-4777-9683-55a8b8c6e59c","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:11:43.985Z","parentId":"7776c502-eca3-40bd-9697-38ba54b0685a"}
